# Security & Safety Hardening Standard

Engineering guidance, not legal advice. Nothing is "unhackable" — never claim it. Goal:
defense in depth (raise attack cost, shrink surface, assume breach, limit blast radius).

Classify data first, calibrate accordingly: regulated health data (PHI) = highest;
financial IP/credentials = high; children's data = high (collect nothing: local-first,
no backend, no accounts); general consumer/marketing = standard.

Core principles: least privilege; minimize attack surface; assume breach; secure by
default / fail closed; defense in depth; never trust the client (enforce server-side,
never ship secrets in client code).

Baseline (all tiers): secrets in env vars never committed; security headers (CSP/HSTS);
parameterized queries + input validation; tokenized payments; rate limiting on public
endpoints; dependency hygiene; server-side authz + MFA on privileged paths.

Higher tiers (PHI/financial/children's): encryption at rest+transit; audit logging with
secrets/PII scrubbed; hard prod/dev isolation with no real data outside prod; signed
vendor data-processing agreements; scoped least-privilege tokens. Verify with adversarial
testing and a real backup restore — don't assert.
